  "myth": {
    "title": "The Oath of the Silver River",
    "text": "
In the highlands of Eldermere, where the Silver River carved its path through the mountains, the people of the village of Veythar honored a sacred covenant. Every generation, the eldest son of the village chief would stand upon the river’s sacred stones at dawn and pledge his life to the river’s spirit, promising to guard its waters and the land it nourished. This was the **Public Vow**, spoken before the gathered villagers, binding the chief’s bloodline to the earth.

The vow was sealed with a **Costly Binding Act**: the young chief would plunge his hand into the river’s icy depths and withdraw a single silver stone—one of the river’s sacred relics. As his fingers closed around it, the stone would burn like fire, marking his palm with a permanent sigil, a reminder of his oath. The pain was said to be the river’s way of ensuring the vow was not taken lightly.

Years passed, and the river’s blessings flowed abundantly. But one chief, **Dain of the Hollow Eyes**, grew greedy. A drought threatened the land, and the people whispered that the river’s spirit was displeased. A traveling merchant offered Dain a **Temptation**: a golden chalice said to summon rain, if only he would break his oath and cast the silver stone into the river’s depths. ‘The river’s spirit is old and weak,’ the merchant hissed. ‘It will not know the difference.’

Dain hesitated, then hurled the stone into the water. That night, the river ran black. The next morning, the villagers awoke to find their crops withered, their wells dry, and Dain’s hand—once marked by the sigil—now **rotted to the bone**. The consequence was swift and unyielding: the river had taken its due. From that day on, the people of Veythar understood the **inevitability of vow-keeping**. The river’s blessing could not be bought or broken; it could only be earned through sacrifice, and its wrath was as eternal as the mountains themselves.
"
  }
}
```

